<h4>Day 7: Get that damn TV out of your bedroom!</h4>
<blockquote class="instagram-media" style="background: #FFF; border: 0; border-radius: 3px; box-shadow: 0 0 1px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.5),0 1px 10px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.15); margin: 1px; max-width: 658px; padding: 0; width: calc(100% - 2px);" data-instgrm-captioned="" data-instgrm-version="5">
<div style="padding: 8px;">
<div style="background: #F8F8F8; line-height: 0; margin-top: 40px; padding: 37.5% 0; text-align: center; width: 100%;"></div>
<p><a href="https://instagram.com/p/8ipuDeIyPQ/" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'https://instagram.com/p/8ipuDeIyPQ/', '#MinimalismTips Day 7: Get that damn TV out of your bedroom! As far as we\'re concerned, a bed has two purposes, neither of which include watching latenight reruns. Look around: we are in the throes of a torrent of multitasking. Everyone is attempting to “increase productivity” in their business and personal lives with their iPhones and iPads and iMacs and iWhatevers. Multitasking is endemic to our culture. But we must accept that no matter how much we multitask, no matter how many concurrent emails and texts and status updates we respond to, we’ll never get everything done. That’s because there’s an infinite amount of tasks to undertake once you’ve “completed everything.” We are constantly bombarded by contemporaneous inputs, and thus it’s more important than ever to find sanctuary in interstitial zones: waiting rooms, the grocery store, and especially the bedroom. Ergo, take back your bedroom. What if you refused to watch TV or surf the web or text message when in bed. Can\'t you do those things elsewhere, another time? Instead, find refuge in knowing that when your head hits the pillow, you’ll either be sleeping or intimate with someone else, but nothing else. There’s comfort in singletasking. Do you have a television in your bedroom? If so, what would your life look like without it?']);" style="color: #000; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; line-height: 17px; text-decoration: none; word-wrap: break-word;"  target="_blank">#MinimalismTips Day 7: Get that damn TV out of your bedroom! As far as we&#8217;re concerned, a bed has two purposes, neither of which include watching latenight reruns. Look around: we are in the throes of a torrent of multitasking. Everyone is attempting to “increase productivity” in their business and personal lives with their iPhones and iPads and iMacs and iWhatevers. Multitasking is endemic to our culture. But we must accept that no matter how much we multitask, no matter how many concurrent emails and texts and status updates we respond to, we’ll never get everything done. That’s because there’s an infinite amount of tasks to undertake once you’ve “completed everything.” We are constantly bombarded by contemporaneous inputs, and thus it’s more important than ever to find sanctuary in interstitial zones: waiting rooms, the grocery store, and especially the bedroom. Ergo, take back your bedroom. What if you refused to watch TV or surf the web or text message when in bed. Can&#8217;t you do those things elsewhere, another time? Instead, find refuge in knowing that when your head hits the pillow, you’ll either be sleeping or intimate with someone else, but nothing else. There’s comfort in singletasking. Do you have a television in your bedroom? If so, what would your life look like without it?</a></p>
<p>A photo posted by The Minimalists (@theminimalists) on <time style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 17px;" datetime="2015-10-07T15:29:24+00:00">Oct 7, 2015 at 8:29am PDT</time>
</div>
</blockquote>
<p><script src="//platform.instagram.com/en_US/embeds.js" async="" defer="defer"></script></p>
<h4>Day 8: Make letting go easy for your entire household—place a donation box in a closet or garage.</h4>
<blockquote class="instagram-media" style="background: #FFF; border: 0; border-radius: 3px; box-shadow: 0 0 1px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.5),0 1px 10px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.15); margin: 1px; max-width: 658px; padding: 0; width: calc(100% - 2px);" data-instgrm-captioned="" data-instgrm-version="5">
<div style="padding: 8px;">
<div style="background: #F8F8F8; line-height: 0; margin-top: 40px; padding: 62.5% 0; text-align: center; width: 100%;"></div>
<p style="margin: 8px 0 0 0; padding: 0 4px;"><a href="https://instagram.com/p/8lh6iCIyPY/" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'https://instagram.com/p/8lh6iCIyPY/', '#MinimalismTips Day 8: Make letting go easy for your entire household—place a donation box in a closet or garage. Show your family how simple it is to get rid of excess stuff when they have access to a donation outlet. Over time, notice how everyone participates if you lead by example. Then, celebrate with a monthly (or weekly) trip to donate your unused items, which someone else can enjoy. How else can you make it easy to donate your unused material possessions?']);" style="color: #000; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; line-height: 17px; text-decoration: none; word-wrap: break-word;"  target="_blank">#MinimalismTips Day 8: Make letting go easy for your entire household—place a donation box in a closet or garage. Show your family how simple it is to get rid of excess stuff when they have access to a donation outlet. Over time, notice how everyone participates if you lead by example. Then, celebrate with a monthly (or weekly) trip to donate your unused items, which someone else can enjoy. How else can you make it easy to donate your unused material possessions?</a></p>
<p style="color: #c9c8cd; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 17px; margin-bottom: 0; margin-top: 8px; overflow: hidden; padding: 8px 0 7px; text-align: center; text-overflow: ellipsis; white-space: nowrap;">A photo posted by The Minimalists (@theminimalists) on <time style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 17px;" datetime="2015-10-08T18:18:55+00:00">Oct 8, 2015 at 11:18am PDT</time></p>
</div>
</blockquote>
<p><script src="//platform.instagram.com/en_US/embeds.js" async="" defer="defer"></script></p>
<h4>Day 9: Slow the fuck down.</h4>
<blockquote class="instagram-media" style="background: #FFF; border: 0; border-radius: 3px; box-shadow: 0 0 1px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.5),0 1px 10px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.15); margin: 1px; max-width: 658px; padding: 0; width: calc(100% - 2px);" data-instgrm-captioned="" data-instgrm-version="5">
<div style="padding: 8px;">
<div style="background: #F8F8F8; line-height: 0; margin-top: 40px; padding: 50.0% 0; text-align: center; width: 100%;"></div>
<p><a href="https://instagram.com/p/8n6WcRoyMB/" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'https://instagram.com/p/8n6WcRoyMB/', '#MinimalismTips Day 9: Slow the fuck down. Take a look around: everyone is “busy.” We’re doing more than we’ve ever done, attempting to fill every interstitial zone with more work. Every downtown scene is the same: heads tilted downward, faces lost in glowing screens, technology turning people into zombies. We live in a busy world, one in which our value is often measured in productivity, efficiency, work rate, output, yield, GTD, the rat race. We are inundated with meetings and spreadsheets and status updates and rush-hour traffic and tweets and conference calls and travel time and text messages and reports and voicemails and multitasking and all the trappings of a busy life. Go, go, go. Busy, busy, busy. Americans are working more hours than ever, but we are actually earning less. Busy has become the new norm. If you’re not busy, especially in today’s workplace, you’re often thought of as lazy, unproductive, inefficient, a waste of space. For us, however, “busy” is a curse word. Henry David Thoreau once said, “It is not enough to be busy. The question is: what are we busy about?” And if we were to append his quandary, we’d say, “It is not enough to be busy. The question is: what are we focused on?” There is a vast difference between being busy and being focused. The former involves the typical tropes of productivity—anything to keep our hands moving, to keep going, to keep the conveyer belt in motion. It is no coincidence we refer to mundane tasks as “busywork.” Busywork works well for factories, robots, and fascism, but not so great for anyone who’s attempting to do something worthwhile with their waking hours. Being focused, on the other hand, involves attention, awareness, and intentionality. Today is Friday—the weekend is upon us. Can we agree to slow down, at least for a while, and focus on what’s truly important?']);" style="color: #000; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; line-height: 17px; text-decoration: none; word-wrap: break-word;"  target="_blank">#MinimalismTips Day 9: Slow the fuck down. Take a look around: everyone is “busy.” We’re doing more than we’ve ever done, attempting to fill every interstitial zone with more work. Every downtown scene is the same: heads tilted downward, faces lost in glowing screens, technology turning people into zombies. We live in a busy world, one in which our value is often measured in productivity, efficiency, work rate, output, yield, GTD, the rat race. We are inundated with meetings and spreadsheets and status updates and rush-hour traffic and tweets and conference calls and travel time and text messages and reports and voicemails and multitasking and all the trappings of a busy life. Go, go, go. Busy, busy, busy. Americans are working more hours than ever, but we are actually earning less. Busy has become the new norm. If you’re not busy, especially in today’s workplace, you’re often thought of as lazy, unproductive, inefficient, a waste of space. For us, however, “busy” is a curse word. Henry David Thoreau once said, “It is not enough to be busy. The question is: what are we busy about?” And if we were to append his quandary, we’d say, “It is not enough to be busy. The question is: what are we focused on?” There is a vast difference between being busy and being focused. The former involves the typical tropes of productivity—anything to keep our hands moving, to keep going, to keep the conveyer belt in motion. It is no coincidence we refer to mundane tasks as “busywork.” Busywork works well for factories, robots, and fascism, but not so great for anyone who’s attempting to do something worthwhile with their waking hours. Being focused, on the other hand, involves attention, awareness, and intentionality. Today is Friday—the weekend is upon us. Can we agree to slow down, at least for a while, and focus on what’s truly important?</a></p>
<p>A photo posted by The Minimalists (@theminimalists) on <time style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 17px;" datetime="2015-10-09T16:30:55+00:00">Oct 9, 2015 at 9:30am PDT</time>
</div>
</blockquote>
