<h4>Day 21: A clean desk is the foundation of a calm workspace.</h4>
<blockquote class="instagram-media" style="background: #FFF; border: 0; border-radius: 3px; box-shadow: 0 0 1px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.5),0 1px 10px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.15); margin: 1px; max-width: 658px; padding: 0; width: calc(100% - 2px);" data-instgrm-captioned="" data-instgrm-version="5">
<div style="padding: 8px;">
<div style="background: #F8F8F8; line-height: 0; margin-top: 40px; padding: 33.1481481481% 0; text-align: center; width: 100%;"></div>
<p><a href="https://instagram.com/p/9Gq4ifIyMr/" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'https://instagram.com/p/9Gq4ifIyMr/', '#MinimalismTips Day 21: A clean desk is the foundation of a calm workspace. We often lie to our selves, pretending we need endless office accoutrements to be “productive.” So we clutter our desks with binders, staplers, Post-it notes, paperclips, thumbtacks, pens, pencils, highlighters, markers, calendars, and dozens of unused office supplies, not to mention the endless stacks of paper we accumulate, all of which leads to a cluttered—and anxiety-producing—workspace. But what if we jettisoned everything unessential? As a experiment, why not give this a shot: get rid of everything today (box it up or simply get it out of the way), and then slowly reintroduce items to your workspace as needed over the next few days. Then get rid of anything you didn’t reintroduce—anything you don’t use this week. It’s like having a miniature #PackingParty for your workspace. With less stuff, it’s so much easier to stay calm, organized, focused. Are you willing to experiment?']);" style="color: #000; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; line-height: 17px; text-decoration: none; word-wrap: break-word;"  target="_blank">#MinimalismTips Day 21: A clean desk is the foundation of a calm workspace. We often lie to our selves, pretending we need endless office accoutrements to be “productive.” So we clutter our desks with binders, staplers, Post-it notes, paperclips, thumbtacks, pens, pencils, highlighters, markers, calendars, and dozens of unused office supplies, not to mention the endless stacks of paper we accumulate, all of which leads to a cluttered—and anxiety-producing—workspace. But what if we jettisoned everything unessential? As a experiment, why not give this a shot: get rid of everything today (box it up or simply get it out of the way), and then slowly reintroduce items to your workspace as needed over the next few days. Then get rid of anything you didn’t reintroduce—anything you don’t use this week. It’s like having a miniature #PackingParty for your workspace. With less stuff, it’s so much easier to stay calm, organized, focused. Are you willing to experiment?</a></p>
<p>A photo posted by The Minimalists (@theminimalists) on <time style="font-family: Arial,sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 17px;" datetime="2015-10-21T15:12:14+00:00">Oct 21, 2015 at 8:12am PDT</time>
